"# Codex Implementation Brief\n\n## Objective\n\nBuild a single-user, client-only todo SPA (React + TypeScript) that is fast, offline-capable, and local-only. Priorities (in order): production reliability, security, maintainability, developer experience.\n\nDo not add features beyond the provided specification. Follow all requirements exactly.\n\n---\n\n## Required Features\n\nImplement the following end-user features exactly as specified:\n\n- Task CRUD (create/read/update/delete) with optimistic UI and rollback on persistence failure.\n- Projects (lists): create, rename, delete with explicit confirmation and Undo. Default delete strategy: unassign tasks (projectId → null). Optional cascade delete with confirmation.\n- Manual reordering of tasks per project using numeric position values, with position averaging and rebalance when necessary.\n- Local persistence with IndexedDB as primary store. Fallbacks: in-memory, then localStorage only as last resort (explicit user consent required).\n- Cross-tab synchronization via BroadcastChannel; fallback to window.storage events.\n- Import / Export: JSON export and import with version metadata; import validated via zod and migrations applied where needed.\n- Optional local encryption (opt-in) using Web Crypto API; passphrase-based key derivation. Warn user about unrecoverable data if passphrase lost.\n- Optional Service Worker to cache static assets for offline app shell; keep SW minimal and safe update flow.\n- UI components include TaskListView, TaskItem, TaskEditor, ProjectManager, Header, Settings, Toast/Undo manager.\n- Accessibility: keyboard navigation, ARIA roles for dialogs and live regions, automated axe checks in CI.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\n\nHigh-level architecture (client-only SPA). Responsibilities and boundaries:\n\n- UI Layer\n  - React components, minimal UI, Tailwind CSS.\n  - Keep UI preferences in React Context.\n\n- State Layer\n  - Global state in Zustand (tasks/projects + selectors).\n  - Local UI state in component state or small React Contexts as needed.\n\n- Service Layer\n  - TaskService and ProjectService:\n    - Perform validation (zod), apply optimistic updates to Zustand, persist via Storage Adapter, emit events.\n    - Throw typed Error subclasses for failures: ValidationError, NotFoundError, StorageUnavailableError, QuotaExceededError, MigrationError.\n\n- Storage Adapter (primary persistence)\n  - idb wrapper with explicit openDB + onupgradeneeded migrations.\n  - Expose well-defined Promise-based API (see \"API Requirements\").\n  - Emit onChange events for local UI updates and cross-tab synchronization input.\n\n- Cross-tab Sync\n  - BroadcastChannel wrapper that sends idempotent mutation envelopes. Ignore messages from same sourceId. Fallback to storage events.\n\n- Import/Export & Backup\n  - Utilities to exportAll(), importAll(), validate payloads, compute basic manifest (counts + checksum).\n\n- Service Worker (optional)\n  - Workbox-based or small manual SW to cache app shell and allow offline load. Keep update flow explicit and user-visible.\n\nAtomicity:\n- Use single IndexedDB transaction for operations touching both tasks and projects. If fallback storage does not support transactions, surface a clear warning before such operations.\n\nOptimistic Updates and Undo:\n- Apply optimistic updates immediately to Zustand, persist to storage, confirm on success, rollback on failure, and surface retry in UI.\n- Soft-delete + Undo timing: default Undo window 8 seconds (implement toast with exact timing configurable in Settings).\n\n---\n\n## Technology Requirements\n\nMandatory technologies and versions:\n\n- React >= 17 + TypeScript (all code in TypeScript).\n- Zustand for global state.\n- idb (tiny IndexedDB wrapper) for DB access, wrapped by Storage Adapter.\n- zod for runtime validation.\n- UUID: uuid v4 (or equivalent).\n- Tailwind CSS (JIT/purge).\n- Vite for bundling/dev.\n- Jest + React Testing Library for unit tests.\n- Playwright (recommended) for E2E across Chromium, Firefox, WebKit; Cypress acceptable alternative but Playwright preferred.\n- fake-indexeddb for Node unit tests.\n- Optional: DOMPurify only if rich text is introduced in future (do not include otherwise).\n- CI: GitHub Actions with lint, unit tests, coverage, security checks (npm audit/Snyk), bundle-size check, E2E matrix, deploy to static host (Vercel/Netlify/GitHub Pages).\n\nSecurity & deploy guidance:\n- Serve via HTTPS.\n- Recommend strict CSP (no inline scripts/styles).\n- Enforce lockfile commit and dependency pinning.\n- Secrets in CI must be in GitHub Actions Secrets only.\n\nCoding Style & Standards:\n- TypeScript types for all public APIs.\n- zod schemas for all runtime validation in Services and Storage Adapter import paths.\n- No use of innerHTML; render all user content escaped as plain text.\n- Use explicit property assignment for updates (no deep merges that may allow prototype pollution).\n- Timestamps: always store ISO 8601 in UTC. Display localized formatting in UI.\n- ARIA roles for dialogs; toasts use live regions.\n- Document all user-facing strings and validation messages for i18n in future.\n\nBundle constraints:\n- Keep production JS bundle under CI threshold (target < 1 MB).\n- Minimize dependencies; avoid heavy UI libraries and icon packs that bloat bundle.\n\n---\n\n## Folder Structure\n\nCreate a canonical folder layout. Each entry indicates expected files and responsibilities.\n\n- src/\n  - api/\n    - services/\n      - TaskService.ts\n      - ProjectService.ts\n      - index.ts (export services)\n    - validators/\n      - schemas.ts (zod schemas for Task, Project, Import payloads)\n  - db/\n    - storageAdapter/\n      - index.ts (StorageAdapter class)\n      - types.ts (StorageChangeEvent, error classes)\n      - migrations/\n        - v1_initial.ts\n        - index.ts (migration registry)\n      - utils.ts (export/import checksum)\n  - state/\n    - store.ts (Zustand store + selectors)\n    - hooks.ts (custom hooks for components)\n  - components/\n    - TaskListView/\n    - TaskItem/\n    - TaskEditor/\n    - ProjectManager/\n    - Header/\n    - Settings/\n    - Toast/\n    - UndoManager/\n  - services/\n    - crossTab/\n      - BroadcastWrapper.ts\n  - utils/\n    - uuid.ts (wrapper)\n    - time.ts (UTC normalize/format)\n    - crypto.ts (WebCrypto helpers for optional encryption)\n  - sw/\n    - service-worker.ts (optional, minimal)\n  - styles/\n    - tailwind.config.js\n  - tests/\n    - unit/\n    - integration/\n    - e2e/\n  - index.tsx\n  - App.tsx\n  - routes.tsx (if using)\n- public/\n  - index.html\n- .github/\n  - workflows/\n    - ci.yml\n    - e2e.yml\n- README.md\n\nNotes:\n- Keep migration files under src/db/storageAdapter/migrations.\n- Place typed error classes in storageAdapter/types.ts for shared import.\n\n---\n\n## Database Requirements\n\nDB name: todo-app\nInitial version: 1\n\nObject stores (all timestamps are ISO 8601 strings):\n\n- projects (keyPath: id)\n  - Required fields: id (UUID v4), name, createdAt, updatedAt\n  - Optional: meta?: { color?: string }\n  - Index: name\n\n- tasks (keyPath: id)\n  - Required: id (UUID v4), title, completed (boolean, default false), createdAt, updatedAt\n  - Optional: description?, dueDate?: string | null (UTC ISO 8601), projectId?: string | null, position?: number\n  - Indexes: projectId, completed, dueDate\n\nPosition / ordering semantics:\n- Use numeric position values (floating-point).\n- When inserting between neighbors, compute position = (posA + posB)/2.\n- Rebalance when positions become too close (loss of precision).\n  - Implementation note (explicit): resequence positions for that project in a single transaction using integers spaced by step = 1000. Example resequencing algorithm:\n    - Sort tasks by current position (or createdAt fallback).\n    - Assign positions: step, 2*step, 3*step, ...\n    - Persist all position writes in the same transaction that triggered the rebalance.\n\nDB migration/versioning policy:\n- Use idb.openDB with onupgradeneeded calling migration step functions for each version increment.\n- Migration step contract:\n  - Validate existing data shape.\n  - Optionally capture a pre-migration snapshot in-memory and return it if migration fails.\n  - Perform in-place transforms within onupgradeneeded transaction if possible; otherwise mark migration failure and preserve DB state for manual recovery.\n- Tests must include migrations from previous versions.\n\nStorage Adapter API (implement exactly these Promise-based signatures):\n\n- openDB(): Promise<void>\n- get(store: 'tasks'|'projects', key: string): Promise<any | null>\n- put(store: 'tasks'|'projects', value: any): Promise<any>\n- delete(store: 'tasks'|'projects', key: string): Promise<void>\n- getAll(store: 'tasks'|'projects', query?: any, direction?: any): Promise<any[]>\n- transaction(stores: string[], mode: 'readonly' | 'readwrite', fn: (tx: IDBTransactionLike) => Promise<void>): Promise<void>\n- onChange(callback: (change: StorageChangeEvent) => void): () => void  // returns unsubscribe\n- exportAll(): Promise<{ version: number; projects: Project[]; tasks: Task[] }>\n- importAll(payload: any): Promise<void>\n\nError types:\n- StorageUnavailableError\n- QuotaExceededError\n- MigrationError\n- ValidationError (use zod for details but throw this class)\n\nFallback policy:\n- If IndexedDB open fails (or operations throw), detect failure reasons and:\n  - If temporary (quota failure on write): throw QuotaExceededError; UI shows remediation guidance and Export option.\n  - If unsupported (e.g., private mode): fallback to in-memory store and inform user that data is not persisted across reloads.\n  - LocalStorage fallback: only use as last resort and only after explicit user consent; store minimal payload or encrypted payload if encryption opted-in.\n\nObservability:\n- StorageAdapter must emit onChange events locally on create/update/delete/migrate with StorageChangeEvent:\n  - { type: 'create' | 'update' | 'delete' | 'migrate', store: string, ids?: string[], timestamp: string, sourceId?: string }\n\nCross-store atomicity:\n- For multi-entity operations (e.g., deleteProject + reassign tasks), use a single IDB transaction across the stores to ensure atomic changes.\n\nExport/import:\n- exportAll must include version metadata and simple manifest: counts and checksum (e.g., SHA-256 over canonical JSON).\n- importAll must validate schemas with zod. If version mismatch, run migrations or prompt user (UI must present migration failure and export option).\n\n---\n\n## API Requirements\n\nAll service APIs are Promise-based and must perform zod validation and safe merges. They must emit onChange events and cross-tab sync messages. Types must be exported.\n\nTaskService API (signatures and behaviors):\n\n- createTask(payload: {\n    title: string;\n    description?: string;\n    dueDate?: string | null;\n    projectId?: string | null;\n    position?: number;\n  }): Promise<Task>\n  - Validate title non-empty, max length.\n  - Validate projectId exists or null.\n  - Assign id (UUID v4), createdAt, updatedAt.\n  - Apply optimistic update to Zustand.\n  - Persist via StorageAdapter.put in a transaction if necessary.\n  - Emit local onChange and BroadcastChannel mutation.\n\n- getTask(id: string): Promise<Task | null>\n\n- listTasks(filter?: {\n    projectId?: string | null;\n    completed?: boolean | 'all';\n    search?: string;\n    sortBy?: 'createdAt' | 'dueDate' | 'position';\n    limit?: number;\n    offset?: number;\n  }): Promise<Task[]>\n  - Search: case-insensitive substring on title and description.\n  - For lists >2000 items, implement virtualization or lazy fetch/pagination.\n\n- updateTask(id: string, updates: Partial<{\n    title: string;\n    description: string | null;\n    dueDate: string | null;\n    projectId: string | null;\n    position: number;\n    completed: boolean;\n  }>): Promise<Task>\n  - Whitelist fields only.\n  - Validate types and projectId target.\n  - Update updatedAt.\n  - If multi-entity changes required (e.g., moving between projects and position updates), perform atomic transaction.\n\n- deleteTask(id: string): Promise<void>\n  - Implement optimistic UI soft-delete with Undo toast (8s default).\n  - Physically delete after Undo window expires.\n  - Persist deletion event; emit onChange.\n\n- toggleComplete(id: string): Promise<Task>\n  - Convenience wrapper updating completed + updatedAt.\n\n- reorderTasks(projectId: string | null, orderedTaskIds: string[]): Promise<void>\n  - Compute positions and persist in a single transaction.\n  - If positions are too close, perform rebalance (see DB section).\n\nProjectService API:\n\n- createProject(payload: { name: string }): Promise<Project>\n- getProject(id: string): Promise<Project | null>\n- listProjects(): Promise<Project[]>\n- updateProject(id: string, updates: Partial<{ name: string }>): Promise<Project>\n- deleteProject(id: string, options?: { strategy?: 'unassign' | 'cascade' | 'prompt'; allowUndo?: boolean }): Promise<void>\n  - Default strategy 'unassign'.\n  - For 'unassign': set projectId=null for tasks in single transaction; show confirmation and Undo toast.\n  - For 'cascade': delete tasks in same transaction; UI must require explicit confirmation and show count of tasks to be removed and offer Undo.\n\nCross-tab sync message envelope (BroadcastChannel messages):\n\n- Envelope shape:\n  - {\n      sourceId: string, // UUID for origin tab\n      opId: string, // UUID for operation\n      op: 'create' | 'update' | 'delete' | 'reorder' | 'migrate',\n      store: 'tasks' | 'projects',\n      payload: { ids?: string[], entity?: any, changes?: any },\n      ts: string // ISO timestamp\n    }\n\n- Receiver must:\n  - Ignore messages from same sourceId.\n  - Ignore messages older than last applied timestamp.\n  - Apply messages idempotently.\n  - Emit local store updates (Zustand) or trigger selective refresh.\n\nOptimistic update contract (explicit steps for implementation):\n\n1. Save pre-operation snapshot of affected entities in memory (to enable rollback).\n2. Apply optimistic update to Zustand immediately (UI reflects change).\n3. Persist through StorageAdapter:\n   - Use transaction for multi-store operations.\n   - On success: emit onChange and BroadcastChannel event with sourceId and opId.\n   - On failure: rollback Zustand to pre-operation snapshot, show friendly error toast with retry option; do not reveal stack traces.\n\nError model:\n- All service functions throw typed Error subclasses. UI maps them to friendly messages.\n- Do not expose internal DB or stack details in messages.\n\nImport/Export contract:\n\n- exportAll(): returns { version: number; projects: Project[]; tasks: Task[]; manifest: { countProjects:number; countTasks:number; checksum:string } }\n- importAll(payload: any): validate via zod:\n  - If version < current: run migrations; if failure, surface error and offer export of pre-migration snapshot.\n  - Handle ID collisions deterministically: preserve IDs from import; if an entity ID already exists, UI import step must decide merge vs replace. (Implement importAll to reject if collision occurs and surface error to UI to request user decision. Do not auto-merge.)\n- All imports must whitelist fields and reject prototype-pollution keys.\n\n---\n\n## Security Rules\n\nStrict security requirements; implement all of these exactly.\n\n1. XSS / Rendering\n  - Render all user content as escaped plain text. Never use innerHTML.\n  - Add unit & E2E tests that assert script payloads do not execute.\n\n2. Input Validation & Prototype Safety\n  - Validate all inputs in Service layer with zod.\n  - Whitelist accepted fields for create/update.\n  - Reject keys like __proto__, constructor, prototype.\n\n3. Local Encryption (optional, opt-in)\n  - Implement optional encryption using Web Crypto API.\n  - Derive key from user passphrase using PBKDF2 with configurable iterations (expose config; choose sane default but ensure documented).\n  - Use AES-GCM for encryption.\n  - Metadata format: include algorithm, salt (base64), iterations, iv (base64) in export manifest.\n  - Warn user: lost password = unrecoverable data.\n  - If encryption enabled, store only encrypted payloads in localStorage fallback.\n\n4. Fallback Storage Handling\n  - Prefer IndexedDB.\n  - LocalStorage used only when explicitly consented to by user and minimized payload stored.\n  - When fallback used, show prominent UI warning.\n\n5. CSP & Hosting Headers\n  - Document recommended CSP and headers in README.\n  - Do not include inline scripts/styles; use hashed or nonce patterns if needed.\n\n6. Dependency Hygiene\n  - Commit lockfile.\n  - CI runs npm audit (or Snyk) and fails on critical/high unless approved.\n\n7. CI Secrets\n  - Use GitHub Actions Secrets for tokens. Do not log secrets.\n\n8. Service Worker\n  - Keep SW minimal. Test update flow to prevent stale served assets.\n\n9. Privacy Disclosure\n  - In Settings & README: inform user data is local and may be synced by browser/OS; provide guidance and encryption option.\n\n10. Error Hygiene\n  - Surface user-friendly errors; never expose raw stack traces or internal DB errors.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Requirements\n\nAll tests must be implemented and wired into CI as specified.\n\nUnit tests (Jest + React Testing Library)\n- Services coverage >= 90%.\n  - Test: TaskService, ProjectService behaviors including validation, optimistic updates, rollback on StorageAdapter failure, zod validation, prototype-pollution attempts.\n- Storage Adapter tests using fake-indexeddb: openDB, migrations, transaction semantics, error paths, fallback policy.\n- Component unit tests: target >= 75% coverage for TaskItem, TaskEditor, ProjectManager, Header.\n- Input rendering tests to assert XSS payloads are escaped.\n\nIntegration tests\n- StorageAdapter + Services together: project deletion with unassign and cascade, reorder + rebalance, multi-entity transactions.\n- Migration tests: simulate older DB versions and assert data correctness after migration.\n\nE2E tests (Playwright recommended)\n- Matrix: Chromium, Firefox, WebKit.\n- Viewports: Desktop, Tablet, Mobile breakpoint.\n- Scenarios:\n  - Full CRUD for tasks & projects; persistence across reload.\n  - Export/import round-trip with migrations.\n  - Project deletion (unassign cascade), confirmation, Undo behavior.\n  - Reordering tasks and position rebalance.\n  - Cross-tab: open two contexts; perform update in one; assert propagation in other.\n  - Quota/IndexedDB failure simulation; verify fallback and UI messaging.\n  - Service Worker offline load & update behavior.\n  - XSS attack vectors: ensure no script execution.\n\nAccessibility Tests\n- Automated axe checks in CI for main pages/components.\n- Manual test checklist for keyboard-only flows and ARIA semantics.\n\nPerformance\n- Synthetic dataset test with ~5k tasks to verify virtualization and responsiveness.\n- Bundle-size check failing CI if target exceeded.\n\nSecurity Tests\n- npm audit/Snyk in CI.\n- Tests verifying no inline scripts/styles in built index.html (CSP compliance).\n- Tests for prototype pollution attempts in services.\n\nCI Pipeline (GitHub Actions recommended)\n- Steps:\n  1. Install dependencies (use lockfile).\n  2. Lint.\n  3. Unit tests + coverage report; enforce coverage thresholds.\n  4. Build.\n  5. Bundle-size check.\n  6. Security scan (npm audit/Snyk).\n  7. E2E matrix (Playwright) on merge to main (and optionally on PRs for UI changes).\n  8. Deploy to static host (with secrets from GitHub Actions Secrets).\n\nTest tooling notes:\n- Use fake-indexeddb in Node unit tests to emulate IndexedDB semantics.\n- E2E must run across three browsers.\n- Include tests for optimistic rollback on simulated QuotaExceededError.\n\n---\n\n## Definition of Done\n\nBefore merge to main and deploy, ensure the following explicit acceptance criteria are met:\n\n1. Task CRUD\n  - Create task with title; view, edit, delete persist across reload/restart.\n  - Optimistic UI + rollback on failure implemented and tested.\n\n2. Projects\n  - Create, rename, delete projects.\n  - Default delete behavior: unassign tasks with confirmation and Undo (Undo toast with 8s default).\n  - Cascade delete option with explicit confirmation and Undo; show count of affected tasks.\n\n3. Persistence & Resilience\n  - IndexedDB persistence works across reload/restart.\n  - App detects IndexedDB unavailability or quota errors and falls back to in-memory or localStorage only after explicit consent.\n  - Export/import works end-to-end. Export includes version metadata.\n\n4. Filtering & Sorting\n  - Filter by project and completion.\n  - Sort by createdAt, dueDate, or manual order (position). Reorder persists and triggers rebalance when needed.\n\n5. Concurrency & Multi-tab\n  - Cross-tab updates propagate (< few seconds) via BroadcastChannel or storage events.\n  - Messages applied idempotently and ignore same-source messages.\n\n6. Offline & Service Worker\n  - Core data operations function offline.\n  - Optional SW allows offline load after first visit. SW update flow tested and user-visible.\n\n7. Security & Privacy\n  - All user text rendered as escaped plain text.\n  - CSP guidance in README.\n  - Optional encryption available and documented (opt-in).\n  - Dependency scanning and CI security checks configured.\n\n8. Reliability & Data Integrity\n  - Migrations implemented and unit-tested.\n  - Atomic transactions for project deletion + task updates.\n  - Undo & optimistic rollback tested.\n\n9. Performance & Bundle Size\n  - App functional and responsive with 5k tasks when using virtualization.\n  - Production bundle size check passes (< configured threshold; target < 1 MB).\n\n10. Testing & CI\n  - CI configured to run lint, unit tests (coverage), build, bundle-size check, security scan, and E2E matrix on merge to main.\n\n11. Documentation\n  - README contains setup/build/test/deploy instructions, export/import, backup guidance, privacy caveats, and optional encryption instructions.\n  - In-app Settings includes Export data, Import data, About storage notes, and browser sync/backups indication.\n\nDeveloper handoff checklist (explicit):\n\n- Implement Storage Adapter and expose typed error classes.\n- Implement TaskService & ProjectService with zod validation, optimistic update/rollback, cross-tab emission.\n- Implement Zustand store and selectors; integrate with optimistic update flows.\n- Build UI components with accessibility and Undo flows; include Export/Import UI in Settings.\n- Add BroadcastChannel wrapper and multi-tab tests.\n- Configure CI: lint, unit tests, security scan, bundle-size check, Playwright matrix, deploy step using secrets.\n- Add README and in-app Settings documentation.\n\n---\n\nNotes and constraints (explicit reminders)\n\n- No server-side code.\n- No sign-in or third-party cloud sync.\n- Keep dependencies minimal.\n- All code in TypeScript.\n- Avoid innerHTML and any direct DOM injection.\n- Store timestamps in UTC ISO format; display with locale-aware functions.\n- LocalStorage fallback only as last resort and with explicit user consent.\n- Undo window default: 8 seconds (configurable in Settings).\n- Secrets must never be committed.\n\n---\n\nAppendix: Explicit Interfaces & Types (implement exactly)\n\nType aliases/interfaces to include in code:\n\n- interface Task {\n    id: string;\n    title: string;\n    description?: string;\n    completed: boolean;\n    dueDate?: string | null; // ISO 8601 UTC\n    projectId?: string | null;\n    position?: number;\n    createdAt: string;\n    updatedAt: string;\n  }\n\n- interface Project {\n    id: string;\n    name: string;\n    createdAt: string;\n    updatedAt: string;\n    meta?: { color?: string };\n  }\n\n- StorageChangeEvent:\n  - { type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'migrate', store: string, ids?: string[], timestamp: string, sourceId?: string }\n\n- Broadcast message envelope:\n  - { sourceId: string, opId: string, op: string, store: string, payload: any, ts: string }\n\n- Error subclasses:\n  - class ValidationError extends Error { details: any }\n  - class NotFoundError extends Error {}\n  - class StorageUnavailableError extends Error {}\n  - class QuotaExceededError extends Error {}\n  - class MigrationError extends Error { snapshot?: any }\n\nImplement these interfaces and error classes in a shared types/errors module for reuse.\n\n---\n\nThis brief contains the explicit, implementable instructions to produce the MVP defined by the consensus specification. Build exactly to these requirements; do not modify or add features beyond what is described."